News producer Beth Knobel illustrates through empirical data how the amount of deep watchdog reporting on the newspapers' studied front pages generally increased over time despite shrinking circulations, low advertising revenue, and pressure to produce the kind of soft news that plays well on social media. Based on the first content analysis to focus specifically on accountability journalism nationally, The Watchdog Still Barks examines the front pages of nine newspapers located across the United States to paint a broad portrait of how public service journalism has changed since 1991 as the advent of the Internet transformed journalism. This portrait of the modern newspaper industry shows how papers of varying sizes and ownership structures around the country marshaled resources for accountability reporting despite significant financial and technological challenges.The Watchdog Still Barks includes original interviews with editors who explain why they are staking their papers' futures on the one thing that American newspapers still do better than any other segment of the media: watchdog and investigative reporting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aGovernment accountabilityzUnited States. 0aJournalismxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aOnline journalismxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aPress and politicszUnited States. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Journalism.2bisacsh  aFree press.  ainvestigative journalism.  ajournalism.  anewspapers.  areporters.  awatchdog.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311072900940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823279364zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823279364423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823279364.jpg  a978-3-11-07290